        "## Ethics"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Our project uses publicly available, aggregated country-level data, which minimizes individual privacy concerns. However, several ethical considerations apply:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Ecological fallacy risk:** Our analysis operates at the country level. It would be irresponsible to use these findings to make claims about individual caffeine consumption and health. We must be transparent that country-level correlations do not imply individual-level causation.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Cultural sensitivity:** Caffeine consumption patterns are deeply tied to culture (e.g., tea ceremonies in East Asia, coffee culture in Scandinavia). Framing any pattern as \"better\" or \"worse\" based on caffeine source could reinforce cultural biases.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Data representativeness:** Model-based estimates from IHME/GBD may be less reliable for low-income countries with weaker health surveillance systems, potentially biasing results toward patterns observed in well-studied, high-income nations.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Potential for misuse:** Findings could be taken out of context by the caffeine/beverage industry for marketing purposes. We emphasize that this is an observational, ecological study and no causal claims should be derived from it."
      ]
    },
